  "text": "Proof In this proof, for ease of presentation, the briber's preferred candidate is called c 1 . Moreover, for every voter v i , we denote by costs i (c j ) the costs to bribe v i such that c j becomes his favorite candidate. We show Theorem 3 by construction of a flow network that can be solved with a minimum cost flow algorithm (which also maximizes the flow in polynomial time, cf. Ahuja et al. [CITATION_1] ), similarly as initially proposed by Faliszewski [CITATION_2] . This method has proven to be useful for showing tractability for many voting problems and is also used by Mattei et al. [CITATION_3] . For each r ∈ {1, . . . , n}, we check if the voters can be bribed with budget β such that the preferred candidate c 1 wins with a score of r votes. If this is possible for at least one r, then we accept, otherwise we reject. For each 1 ≤ r ≤ n, we define a flow network consisting of a source node s, a target node t, and the following sets of nodes and directed edges. All edges have costs 0 and capacity 1, unless specified otherwise.",
